Description of Events: Michael Middleton with the DHL Express DCA Service Center contacted our Hotline to report a leaking Dangerous Goods in Excepted Quantities shipment in their warehouse. Prior to his call  the shipment had been placed into a large plastic bin to contain the leak and the plastic bin had been moved to the haz area.  PSC Environmental was contacted and spill responders were dispatched to DCA Service Center.  Upon their arrival  the shipment was discovered to contain 8 x 1 liter glass bottles of UN1170  PG II.  Due to the lack of cushioning material in the shipment  1 glass bottle broke  leaking its entire contents. The area was cleaned and the shipment was bagged and placed into a salvage drum.  The shipment was marked and labeled as Dangerous Goods in Excepted Quantities.  The contents exceed what is allowed to ship as Dangerous Goods in Excepted Quantities.

ON JUNE 4  1992  B. SAMPLES  M. MCGINNIS  S. SOMMER AND B. HOLLIS MET USAIR FLIGHT 1710.  THE PASSENGER BAGS WERE OFFLOADED FROM THE REAR BIN. B. HOLLIS BEN DROVE A BELT LOADER UP THE FORWARD BIN.  M. MCGINNIS OPENED THE BIN DOOR AND CLIMBED INSIDE.  B. HOLLIS WALKED UP TO THE DOOR INQUIRING IF THERE WERE ANY BAGS.  M. MCGINNIS SAID NO  BUT HER EYES WERE BURNING.  B. HOLLIS TOLD HER TO CLIMB OUT AND HE WOULD GET IN.  AFTER DOING SO  HIS EYES BEGAN TO BURN.  HE CLIMBED OUT AND TOLD THE MAIN RUNNER (S. SOMMER)  AND THEN HE WALKED TO THE REAR AND ADVISED B. SAMPLES.  S. SOMMER PULLED HIS TUG UP TO THE BELT LOADER TO GET READY TO ASSIST WITH OFFLOADING THE MAIL B. SAMPLES WAS INFORMED THAT THERE WAS A NASTY SMELL IN THE FRONT BIN.  HE WENT TO THE FRONT BIN  JUMPED IN  AND QUICKLY JUMPED BACK OUT TO THE GROUND WITH HIS EYES WATERING AND GASPING FOR BREATH.  S. SOMMER PICKED UP THE RED SACK OF MAIL  THE BOTTOM OF THE BAG WAS SOAKED WITH SOME SORT OF CHEMICAL.  HE COULD SMELL FUMES ERE IRRITATING TO HIS EYE.  B. SAMPLES REQUESTED THE FIRE DEPT'S HELP IN CHECKING IT OUT.

Description of Events: WHILE TIPPING DRUM IN PREPARATION FOR UNLOADING FROM TRUCK  DRIVER NOTICED A SMALL AMOUNT OF ACID TRICKLING FROM A CRACK IN THE SIDE OF THE TOP OF THE DRUM.  THE DRIVER RETURNED THE LEAKING DRUM TO THE UPRIGHT POSITION  IN WHICH IT WAS NOT LEAKING  AND OFFLOADED THE REMAINING DRUMS IN THE CUSTOMER'S SHIPMENT.  THE DRIVER THEN SECURED THE DEFECTIVE DRUM IN THE TRUCK  SPREAD SODA ASH AROUND THE BOTTOM OF THE DRUM TO ABSORB AND NEUTRALIZE ANY ACID THAT MIGHT ESCAPE FROM THE CRACK DUE TO JOSTLING DURING TRANSPORTATION. IT IS NOT KNOWN WHAT CAUSED THE PACKAGING FAILURE.  THE SUPERVISOR SUGGESTED TWO POSSIBLE CAUSES: PACKAGE FAILURE DUE TO AGE  OR PACKAGE FAILURE DUE TO IMPROPER BANDING.  (DRUMS ON PALLETS ARE BANDED TOGETHER FOR STABILITY.  IF THE DRUMS  REPEATEDLY  WERE BANDED TO TIGHTLY TO ALLOW FOR PRODUCT EXPANSION DUE TO TEMPERATURE CHANGES  INTERNAL PRESSURE MAY HAVE WEAKENED THE SEAMS). RECOMMENDATIONS TO IMPROVE HANDLING: 1) REMOVE OLDER DRUMS FROM SERVICE  2) INSTRUCT: A) DRUM FILLERS TO CHECK MORE CAREFULLY FOR PACKAGE INTEGRITY BEFORE FILLING  B) LOADER AND DRIVER TO CHECK CAREFULLY FOR PACKAGE INTEGRITY BEFORE LOADING  C) DRUM BANDER TO ALLOW FOR EXPANSION WHEN BANDING PALLETIZED DRUMS.

What Failed Description: Auxiliary Valve; Bottom Outlet Valve; Piping or Fittings
Description of Events: RAILROAD EMPLOYEES OBSERVED LIQUID DRIPPING FROM THE BOTTOM OF TANK CAR GATX90687 AS IT PASSED BY IN THE BENNING YARD.  EMPLOYEES IMMEDIATELY NOTIFIED THE TRAIN DISPATCHER  WHO IN TURN DIRECTED TRAIN Q41507 TO STOP. THE LOCAL FIRE DEPARTMENT WAS NOTIFIED AND RESPONDED.  ONCE THE TRAIN WAS STOPPED  THE FIRE DEPARTMENT HAZMAT TEAM APPROACHED THE CAR AND FOUND THAT THE OUTLET PLUG FOR THE 2  AUXILIARY VALVE WAS OUT AND THE VALVE HANDLE WAS IN THE OPEN POSITION (20% OPEN).  PRODUCT WAS DRIPPING FROM BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE AT THE RATE OF 16-32 OUNCES PER MINUTE.  THE HAZMAT TEAM REPLACED THE OUTLET PLUG AND CLOSED THE VALVE HANDLE.  THIS ABATED THE LEAK AND PRODUCT CEASED TO DRIP.  SUBSEQUENT INSPECTION OF THE INTERNAL TANK VALVE (TOBOV) FOUND THAT THE VALVE ROD TOOK 1/4-1/2 TURNS TO FULLY CLOSE THE VALVE.  THE PACKING NUT ON THE STUFFING BOX HAD TO BE TURNED 1-1/2 TURNS TO FULLY TIGHTEN THE PACKING NUT WITH A WRENCH.  THE AREA BELOW THE LEAKING VALVE WAS WET WITH PRODUCT.  THE IMPACTED RAIL BALLAST WAS REMOVED FOR DISPOSAL. THE TANK CAR WAS MOVED BACK TO THE BENNING YARD (1 MILE AWAY) AND RE-INSPECTED TO ENSURE ALL VALVES AND FITTING WERE CLOSED AND SECURE.  THE INSPECTION FOUND ALL VALVES AND FITTINGS SECURE  AND THE CAR WAS RELEASED FOR MOVEMENT TO THE CONSIGNEE.

Description of Events: AT APPROXIMATELY 11:30 AM ON THURSDAY APRIL 27  2006 EMPLOYEE (CHERRY HILL FUEL TRUCK DRIVER) DISCOVERED THAT HER FUEL TRUCK NUMBER 338  WHICH WAS PARKED ON THE EASTBOUND SIDE OF VAN NESS STREET N.W. WASHINGTON  D.C. HAD BEGUN TO LEAK DIESEL FUEL. EMPLOYEE INDICATED THAT SHE HAD COMPLETED FUELING EQUIPMENT ON THE SITE AND LEFT HER TRUCK PARKED ON THE EASTBOUND SIDE OF VAN NESS STREET WHILE SHE WENT UP TO THE CHERRY HILL OFFICE TRAILER. SHE WAS WALKING BACK TO HER TRUCK FROM THE TRAILER AND WAS AT THE INTERSECTION OF INTERNATIONAL DRIVE AND VAN NESS WHEN SHE NOTICED THE LEAK. UPON INVESTIGATION  EMPLOYEE DISCOVERED THAT THE LEAK WAS CAUSED BY FAILURE OF A HOSE COUPLING ON THE LINE FROM THE MAIN TANK TO THE PUMP. THE LEAK ORIGINATED AROUND THE COUPLING AND THERE WAS NOT A “HOLE” IN THE LINE IT WOULD BE BETTER DESCRIBED AS A SEPARATION OF THE METAL COUPLING FROM THE LINE. THE ESTIMATED DURATION OF THE RELEASE IS 8-10 MINUTES. THE ABSORBENT THAT WAS STORED ON THE FUEL TRUCK WAS DEPLOYED IMMEDIATELY.     OTHER CHERRY HILL PERSONNEL RESPONDED IMMEDIATELY TO CONTAIN THE SPILLED FUEL. ANOTHER MALE EMPLOYEE (CHERRY HILL SUPERINTENDENT) HAD THE ON-SITE SPILL KIT BROUGHT TO THE SCENE AND DEPLOYED MORE ABSORBENT AS WELL AS ABSORBENT PADS. AT APPROXIMATELY 11:40 AM MALE EMPLOYEE CALLED ME TO NOTIFY ME OF THE SPILL. I ASKED HIM IF HE WANTED ME TO BRING THE SPILL KIT FROM OUR TAYLOR STREET BRIDGE PROJECT AND HE RESPONDED IN THE AFFIRMATIVE. I LOADED THE SPILL KIT AND PROCEEDED TOWARD THE CHINA EMBASSY PROJECT. I CALLED MY SUPERVISOR (CHERRY HILL SAFETY DIRECTOR) TO NOTIFY HIM OF THE SPILL AND HE INFORMED ME THAT HE WAS ALREADY AWARE OF THE SPILL AND THAT CLEAN VENTURES (CLEAN-UP CONTRACTOR) HAD ALREADY BEEN NOTIFIED AND WAS PREPARING TO RESPOND TO THE SPILL.    AT APPROXIMATELY 12:10-12:15 PM I ARRIVED ON THE SCENE. I NOTED THE FUEL TRUCK WAS PARKED JUST EAST OF THE SITE ACCESS CLOSEST TO THE SINGAPORE EMBASSY AND A STREAM OF FUEL HAD TRAVELED FROM THE TRUCK DOWNHILL TOWARD CONNECTICUT AVENUE. I ALSO NOTED CHERRY HILL PERSONNEL SPREADING ABSORBENT IN THE INTERSECTION OF INTERNATIONAL DRIVE AND VAN NESS.     THE ABSORBENT AND PADS FROM THE SPILL KIT I BROUGHT WERE IMMEDIATELY PLACED ON THE FUEL IN THE INTERSECTION OF INTERNATIONAL DRIVE AND VAN NESS. AS THE ABSORBENT WAS BEING PLACED I HEARD SIRENS FROM DCFD EQUIPMENT.     ONCE DCFD ARRIVED I SOUGHT OUT THE INCIDENT COMMANDER (BATTALION CHIEF - NO NAME) TO NOTIFY HIM THAT DCFD SHOULD CHECK THE OUTFALL OF THE STORM SEWER FOR POSSIBLE FUEL. HE SENT DCFD PERSONNEL TO SOAPSTONE TO CHECK ON THE STATUS AND BASED UPON THE FACT THAT CHERRY HILL WAS ACTIVELY CLEANING THE SPILL AND HAD A CLEAN-UP CONTRACTOR ON THE WAY HE REMOVED THE DCFD EQUIPMENT AND PERSONNEL FROM THE SCENE. THE CAPT. (SOD BATTALION CHIEF) REMAINED ON THE SCENE. HE ADVISED THAT HE IS RESPONSIBLE FOR THE BATTALION THAT INCLUDES HAZMAT. ADDITION CHERRY HILL PERSONNEL AND ABSORBENT MATERIALS ARRIVED ON-SITE.     ANOTHER CHERRY HILL FUEL TRUCK NUMBER 343 AR

Description of Events: Driver is directed by a consignee employee at to where to unload and into what   storage tank. The driver had paperwork that requires the customer representative to  sign prior to off-loading that states that their storage tank has the capacity to hold the shipment. The driver's responsibility during the off-loading is with the vehicle. The consignee employee's responsibility is to monitor the storage tank level.  The storage tank is out of the drivers view so when the tank level gets to a critical point the employee is to signal to the driver to stop the off-load.  The tank overflowed because the consignee employee assigned to monitor their storage tank left the area. Liquid level in the storage tank raised to a critical point and because air pressure is used to unload the tank trailer some of that pressure pushed the level even higher and some material vented out of the tank into a containment area. The material was cleaned up by plant employees.

Description of Events: Driver hooked up hoses to pump from IBC into customer tank. Driver checked all connections again and turned on pump. Driver started to walk away to make sure product was going into customer tank. He was about 15ft. away when he turned around and saw acid spraying from the connection at the discharge hose and pump. Driver turned off the pump to stop the product from spraying. The customer employees and driver started spreading soda ash to neutralize and contain the acid. The driver then turned off all valves and disconnected the hoses. When the driver disconnected the hoses  he saw that one of the metal ears of the 1.5  dry mate valve had broken in half causing the leak. DC Hazmat and Fire showed up on scene to take over. Environmental clean up team called in the clean up the spill.

AT APPROXIMATELY 0800 THE FEDEX IADR-DCAA TRACTOR/TRAILER SHUTTLE DRIVER POSITIONED HIS VEHICLE TO BACK INTO THE DCAA DOCK AREA. HE NOTICED SMOKE COMING FROM THE BACK OF THE TRAILER AND THEN DISCONNECTED HIS TRACTOR AND PULLED IT INTO A SAFE LOCATION.  HE THEN WENT TO THE BACK OF THE TRAILER AND OPENED DOORS ONLY TO FIND THAT THE SMOKE WAS TOO HEAVY TO ATTEMPT CONTAINMENT WITH HIS VEHICLE FIRE EXTINGUISHER.  THE WASHINGTON  DC FIRE DEPARTMENT RESPONDED AND EXTINGUISHED THE TRAILER FIRE WITHOUT FURTHER INCIDENT.  ACCORDING TO THE DANGEROUS GOODS MANIFEST FORM THAT WAS TAKEN FROM THE TRACTOR  THERE WERE NO DECLARED DANGEROUS GOODS IN THIS TRAILER. I NOTIFIED THE FAA ABOUT THIS INCIDENT  SINCE SOME OF THE FREIGHT ON THIS TRAILER WAS FREIGHT THAT HAD FLOWN TO THE FEDEX IADR RAMP FACILITY AND BECAUSE OF THE POSSIBILITY THAT THIS FIRE COULD HAVE BEEN STARTED BY A HIDDEN DANGEROUS GOODS SHIPMENT.  FEDEX SAFETY IN THE WASHINGTON  DC AREA IS CONDUCTING AN INVESTIGATION INTO THIS INCIDENT.
